para.p:
The inference of stellar ages, masses, and radii has improved through the use of asteroseismology in recent years (e.g. see the review by 
            , 
          ). Measuring the oscillation modes in stars using photometric time series data, from missions such as CoRoT (
            , 
          ), Kepler (
            , 
          ), and TESS (
            , 
          ) has given us new insights into the structure and evolution of stars (
            , 
          ). Recent examples include a deeper understanding of stellar structure (
            , 
          ), chronology of a Milky Way merger (
            , 
          ), and classifying exoplanetary systems (
            , 
          ). Several studies used grids of stellar models with constraints from asteroseismology to produce catalogues of precise stellar parameters (
            , 
          ). However, with increasing precision on fundamental parameters inferred from stellar models with asteroseismology, extra care should be taken to ensure that we are accounting for uncertainty in our choice of stellar physics.

The use of HBMs has been demonstrated in other areas of astrophysics to reduce individual parameter uncertainties by encoding prior information about the distribution of the parameter in a population. For example, HBMs have been used with data from Gaia, improving distance measures (
            , 
          ) and calibrating the red clump as a standard candle (
            , 
          ) using asteroseismology (
            , 
          ). In other instances, HBMs have been used to infer binary-star and exoplanet eccentricities (
            , 
          ), obliquity of transit systems (
            , 
          ), stellar inclination with asteroseismology (
            , 
          ), and the age-metallicity relation of the solar neighbourhood (
            , 
          ).

Our HBM requires a way to map from the stellar initial (or bulk) properties to predict observables. We can achieve this with a large grid of stellar evolutionary models. However, a discrete grid can produce inaccurate posterior distributions, limited to the grid resolution. Increasing the resolution is computationally demanding, especially when scaling to higher input dimensions. One solution is to interpolate the stellar models, as is common in the isochrone-fitting method (see e.g. 
            , 
          ). However, interpolation can become computationally expensive at high input dimensions and grid size, and evaluating the likelihood using modern Bayesian sampling techniques is slow. Therefore, we use machine learning to map stellar model inputs to observables to provide a fast way to sample the HBM. In this work, we train an artificial neural network (ANN) on a large grid of stellar models. There have been similar applications of ANNs in asteroseismology (
            , 
          ) but not yet in the context of an HBM. Using the machine learning speed-up, we demonstrate a scalable method for obtaining fundamental stellar parameters.

