para.p:
Including all-sky data from TESS and in anticipation of PLATO (
            , 
          ) we can expect our sample size of asteroseismic dwarfs and subgiants only to increase. There is also scope to extend our grid of models to include red giants, for which there are vast catalogues of stars already studied with Kepler (
            , 
          ).

Once we constructed our grid of models, we needed a way in which we could continuously sample the grid for use in our statistical model. We opted to train an ANN. The ANN is advantageous over interpolation because it scales well with dimensionality, training and evaluation is fast, and gradient evaluation is easy due to its roots in linear algebra (
            , 
          ). We trained an ANN on the data generated by the grid of stellar models to map fundamentals to observables. Firstly, we split the grid into a train and validation dataset for tuning the ANN, as described in Appendix . We then tested a multitude of ANN configurations and training data inputs, repeatedly evaluating them with the validation dataset in Appendix . In Appendix , we reserved a set of randomly generated, off-grid stellar models as our final test dataset to evaluate the approximation ability of the best-performing ANN independently from our train and validation data. Here, we briefly describe the theory and motivation behind the ANN.

We evaluated the performance of three activation functions: the hyperbolic-tangent, the rectified linear unit (ReLU; 
              , 
            ) and the exponential linear unit (ELU; 
              , 
            ). Although the ReLU activation function out-performed the other two in speed and accuracy, the resulting ANN output was not smooth. The discontinuity in the ReLU function, 


